WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.442 --> 00:00:09.150
MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon, and welcome

00:00:09.150 --> 00:00:13.120
to "Talks at Google" in
Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:18.270
Today it's my great pleasure
to introduce Dr. Damon Tweedy.

00:00:18.270 --> 00:00:22.075
Dr. Tweedy is a graduate of
Duke Medical School where

00:00:22.075 --> 00:00:24.584
his first day was
uncomfortably exciting,

00:00:24.584 --> 00:00:29.310
but not in a good Google
way, Yale Law School.

00:00:29.310 --> 00:00:32.354
He is Assistant Professor of
Psychiatry at Duke University

00:00:32.354 --> 00:00:36.266
Medical School and staff
physician at the Durham VA

00:00:36.266 --> 00:00:38.138
Medical Center.

00:00:38.138 --> 00:00:40.730
He is the author of
one of the most talked

00:00:40.730 --> 00:00:42.550
about books of
this season and one

00:00:42.550 --> 00:00:45.080
of my favorite
books of the year,

00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:48.500
"Black Man in a White Coat:
A Doctor's Reflections

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:50.870
on Race and Medicine."

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:53.942
Writing this book is part
of his ongoing effort

00:00:53.942 --> 00:00:56.890
to honor the pioneering
work of black physicians

00:00:56.890 --> 00:01:00.758
of previous generations
by giving to the community

00:01:00.758 --> 00:01:02.670
as they have done.

00:01:02.670 --> 00:01:04.739
Dr. Tweedy's
training and practice

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:06.985
has shown him the
challenges faced

00:01:06.985 --> 00:01:09.815
by black doctors and
the health burdens faced

00:01:09.815 --> 00:01:15.040
by black patients, why being
black is bad for your health.

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:19.144
Along the way he's overcome
his own biases, as well as

00:01:19.144 --> 00:01:22.853
those from physicians and
patients of all colors.

00:01:22.853 --> 00:01:26.560
He's here today to share
with us what he's learned

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:29.028
and his suggestions for
how we might move forward

00:01:29.028 --> 00:01:33.580
with better treatment and more
compassionate care for all.

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:36.833
Please join me in
welcoming Dr. Damon Tweedy.

00:01:36.833 --> 00:01:38.791
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:38.791 --> 00:01:39.791
DAMON TWEEDY: Thank you.

00:01:43.250 --> 00:01:44.120
Thank you.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:46.740
Thanks for everyone
for coming today.

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:49.500
Yeah, so it's funny
to hear Google.

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:51.090
My first thought
when I here Google

00:01:51.090 --> 00:01:55.130
is that I have this sort
of connection to Google.

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:58.100
Sergey Brin is
actually from Maryland,

00:01:58.100 --> 00:02:01.440
and briefly we've attended
the same high school,

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:03.790
actually, and in the
same magnet program.

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:05.540
I'll tell you a little
bit more about that

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:06.581
when I tell you my story.

00:02:06.581 --> 00:02:08.210
And we didn't actually
know each other.

00:02:08.210 --> 00:02:10.001
Maybe I should've picked
my friends better.

00:02:10.001 --> 00:02:12.005
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:12.005 --> 00:02:12.680
But yeah.

00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:13.890
So I'll tell you a little
more about that high school,

00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:16.098
because that's really an
important part of my journey

00:02:16.098 --> 00:02:18.200
as to who I am today.

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:18.700
OK.

00:02:18.700 --> 00:02:20.024
So this is the book.

00:02:20.024 --> 00:02:21.690
Here's the cover of
the book, "Black Man

00:02:21.690 --> 00:02:23.870
a White Coat: A
Doctor's Reflections

00:02:23.870 --> 00:02:24.940
on Race and Medicine."

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:26.100
So I guess the first
thought is that there's

00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:28.516
so many books out there, so
why should you read this book?

00:02:28.516 --> 00:02:30.810
What's in it for you?

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:33.020
Race is all over the news.

00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:34.410
You hear about
race all the time.

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:36.840
It's often talked about
in law enforcement.

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:39.101
It's talked about in
crime and punishment.

00:02:39.101 --> 00:02:41.350
Those are the areas we hear
it talk about so much now.

00:02:41.350 --> 00:02:43.580
But race is also an
important issue in medicine.

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:45.550
It's an important issue
in medicine as well.

00:02:45.550 --> 00:02:48.260
And I wanted to give you a
quote from Martin Luther King

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:49.880
Jr. It was in 1966.

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:52.250
And this is just sort
of to set the framework.

00:02:52.250 --> 00:02:54.560
So this is 1966, two years
after the Civil Rights

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:56.560
Act had passed, one year
after the Voting Rights

00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:57.660
Act had passed.

00:02:57.660 --> 00:03:00.700
And his quote was, "Of all
the forms of inequality,

00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:03.880
injustice in health
is the most shocking

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:05.859
and the most inhumane."

00:03:05.859 --> 00:03:07.650
To me, that speaks to
this idea that health

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:10.160
is so important to all of
us, vital to all of us.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:11.940
I think he also was
getting to this idea

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:13.570
that health is about more
than simply the health

00:03:13.570 --> 00:03:15.960
care and the medical treatment,
and so many other factors

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:19.320
in society also
influence health.

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:22.060
So there are really two ways
that the book approaches

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:22.760
this issue.

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:24.932
One is about the issue of
African American patients

00:03:24.932 --> 00:03:25.640
and their health.

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:27.615
And there are all sorts
of health disparities

00:03:27.615 --> 00:03:28.990
that are out there,
and I'm going

00:03:28.990 --> 00:03:30.880
to talk a little bit about
that in a few minutes.

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:32.879
And then there's also
there's another experience

00:03:32.879 --> 00:03:36.720
about being an African American
physician and being one of few.

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:39.900
So nationwide, about
4% of all physicians

00:03:39.900 --> 00:03:41.055
are African American.

00:03:41.055 --> 00:03:43.630
The population of African
American is about 13%.

00:03:43.630 --> 00:03:45.310
And in some
specialties-- it varies

00:03:45.310 --> 00:03:46.540
depending on the medical
specialty that you're

00:03:46.540 --> 00:03:47.740
in-- it can be 1% or 2%.

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:48.970
It just depends on the field.

00:03:48.970 --> 00:03:52.407
So you're really
kind of out there.

00:03:52.407 --> 00:03:54.240
You're really sort of
isolated in many ways.

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:57.290
And so the book really
explores those two areas.

00:03:57.290 --> 00:04:00.520
So I set the framework
using the quote from King

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:03.060
about race in society,
but this is really

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:05.160
very much more personal story.

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.227
So many years ago-- he mentioned
that I went to Yale Law School.

00:04:08.227 --> 00:04:09.810
And maybe years ago
I may have written

00:04:09.810 --> 00:04:12.630
a book that was much more
policy-oriented solutions.

00:04:12.630 --> 00:04:15.840
Let's attack these problems,
data-driven, solution-driven.

00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:17.690
This is very much
a personal story.

00:04:17.690 --> 00:04:20.720
This is very much
how I came at it.

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:23.350
I enjoy books by doctors,
and so many of the books

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:25.730
that I read going through
medical school and my training,

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:27.420
so few of them talked
about race at all.

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:29.711
And when they did mention
race, it was only in passing.

00:04:29.711 --> 00:04:31.830
But it was such an
important issue to me,

00:04:31.830 --> 00:04:34.660
and I wanted to give voice
to this other perspective

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:36.560
out there.

00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:38.480
So some of the people
who have-- so my book

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:40.020
has gotten really
good reception.

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:41.120
I've actually really
been overwhelmed

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:42.800
by the positive attention
that I've gotten.

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:45.341
Media coverage, all those things
that I never really imagined

00:04:45.341 --> 00:04:46.800
when I first got started.

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:48.270
But it has had some criticism.

00:04:48.270 --> 00:04:49.686
And the criticism
that I've gotten

00:04:49.686 --> 00:04:53.200
is specifically about that, that
it's not policy-oriented, not

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:55.080
solution-driven.

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:56.789
But I do talk about
many of those issues.

00:04:56.789 --> 00:04:58.579
But even though that's
not the focus of it,

00:04:58.579 --> 00:05:01.030
I still think there's a lot
to learn from this book.

00:05:01.030 --> 00:05:02.710
I'm using my own story and
the stories of other people

00:05:02.710 --> 00:05:03.650
that I've seen, patients.

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:04.870
And I think there's
a lot of ways

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:06.036
that we can learn from that.

00:05:06.036 --> 00:05:08.339
And people can come up
with their own answers.

00:05:08.339 --> 00:05:10.880
So that's really kind of where
I'm coming from in this story.

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:12.570
But we will talk about some
of the more concrete stuff

00:05:12.570 --> 00:05:13.530
as well.

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:16.020
So I think since I set the
framework of this being a very

00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:17.460
personal story, I think it's
helpful to know a little bit

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:19.080
about my background.

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:20.790
So I grew up in Maryland.

00:05:20.790 --> 00:05:23.710
And the county's called
Prince George's County.

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:26.420
It's about 10 minutes
east of Washington, DC.

00:05:26.420 --> 00:05:28.775
Now it's a predominately
African American county,

00:05:28.775 --> 00:05:30.650
and there's been books
written about it where

00:05:30.650 --> 00:05:32.780
they talk about it as
a very affluent, very

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:34.690
wealthy community for
African Americans.

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:36.730
Now there is a part of the
county where that's the case,

00:05:36.730 --> 00:05:38.521
but that's certainly
not where I came from.

00:05:38.521 --> 00:05:41.810
So I came from the part that's
much closer to the Washington,

00:05:41.810 --> 00:05:43.000
DC line.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.185
All black, very segregated,
very working class.

00:05:46.185 --> 00:05:47.560
Really there were
very few models

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:49.310
of African Americans
in that community who

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:52.790
succeeded outside of the sports
and kind of entertainment

00:05:52.790 --> 00:05:55.160
around that we're so often
familiar seeing African

00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:56.160
Americans succeeding in.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:58.000
So as far as going
to college, just

00:05:58.000 --> 00:05:59.583
going to college as
a student, I mean,

00:05:59.583 --> 00:06:01.620
that was a really alien
concept in the community

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:02.810
that I grew up in.

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:04.190
Black men were much more
likely to find themselves

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:06.523
in the criminal justice system
and all those other sorts

00:06:06.523 --> 00:06:09.650
of things that we all
to often hear about.

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:12.160
So my parents did
not go to college.

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:15.004
My dad didn't even
finish high school.

00:06:15.004 --> 00:06:16.170
I did have an older brother.

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:17.100
My brother's ten
years older than me.

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:18.040
And he did go to college.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:19.960
He was one of the first people
in my family to attend college.

00:06:19.960 --> 00:06:21.460
Went to the University
of Maryland.

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:23.040
And he was there just
strictly on academics.

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:24.310
And I was just a novel thing.

00:06:24.310 --> 00:06:27.250
So for me to have that in
my home was a huge example.

00:06:27.250 --> 00:06:29.000
But even still, the
idea of being a doctor

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.480
was something that was
still far beyond what

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:31.880
I could have ever envisioned.

00:06:31.880 --> 00:06:34.100
So in eighth grade I
was in middle school.

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:38.400
A very sort of average, real
average kind of middle school.

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:40.619
90%, 95% African American.

00:06:40.619 --> 00:06:42.160
And one day a teacher,
a math teacher

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:44.701
said, well, you should try and
take this test for this magnet

00:06:44.701 --> 00:06:45.890
program.

00:06:45.890 --> 00:06:47.110
You might be able to make it.

00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:48.522
And my first thought was, no.

00:06:48.522 --> 00:06:49.230
I'm thinking, no.

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:50.730
I'm not going to
be able to do that.

00:06:50.730 --> 00:06:52.980
No one I know has done that.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:57.240
But I took one of the flyers,
and I got into this program.

00:06:57.240 --> 00:06:59.810
This is a very great science
technology magnet program.

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:01.184
And this is actually
the same one

00:07:01.184 --> 00:07:04.040
that Mr. Brin was in as well.

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.630
And so that really kind of
set me on a different path,

00:07:06.630 --> 00:07:07.420
in a way.

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:10.412
And I got to see people
with different aspirations

00:07:10.412 --> 00:07:12.370
and things of that sort,
different experiences.

00:07:12.370 --> 00:07:14.560
So that's sort of how
I got on the trajectory

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:16.060
to where I am today.

00:07:16.060 --> 00:07:17.409
Now it was an appeal to me.

00:07:17.409 --> 00:07:18.450
Like, why being a doctor?

00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:21.140
So there was appeal in
science and medicine.

00:07:21.140 --> 00:07:24.090
So I was really attracted by the
idea of formulas and equations.

00:07:24.090 --> 00:07:27.069
And it was all very objective
and it was sort of concrete.

00:07:27.069 --> 00:07:29.360
So much of life is messy as
an African American person.

00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:31.330
Life in general can be messy,
but as an African American,

00:07:31.330 --> 00:07:32.620
it can be even more messy.

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:34.172
And so there was
a certain appeal

00:07:34.172 --> 00:07:36.755
that science and medicine held
out for me, that was objective,

00:07:36.755 --> 00:07:38.550
it was concrete.

00:07:38.550 --> 00:07:40.640
And I could kind of
escape this other world,

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:41.760
this other reality.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:43.160
And so that's
really what kind of

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:44.990
led me on this path
from high school

00:07:44.990 --> 00:07:47.740
through college and
into medical school.

00:07:47.740 --> 00:07:49.555
But when I got to
medical school,

00:07:49.555 --> 00:07:51.520
I kind of had a rude awakening.

00:07:51.520 --> 00:07:53.620
And so that's really
where the book begins.

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:55.670
it sort of lays that groundwork.

00:07:55.670 --> 00:07:58.402
So I did really well
in college, and I

00:07:58.402 --> 00:08:00.360
had a lot of opportunities
for medical schools.

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:02.010
And I ended up ultimately
deciding on Duke.

00:08:02.010 --> 00:08:03.926
I was deciding between
Duke and Johns Hopkins,

00:08:03.926 --> 00:08:05.940
which was closer to my home.

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:07.844
Duke was at that point
trying to recruit

00:08:07.844 --> 00:08:09.510
more African American
students, and they

00:08:09.510 --> 00:08:11.270
started to offer
scholarships as a way

00:08:11.270 --> 00:08:12.520
to entice African
American students,

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:14.645
because they'd had a long
history of not being able

00:08:14.645 --> 00:08:16.100
to recruit African Americans.

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:17.766
As you can imagine,
it was in the south.

00:08:17.766 --> 00:08:19.370
You can imagine all
the reasons why.

00:08:19.370 --> 00:08:21.130
So let me just read
for a few minutes

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:22.442
the introduction to this
story, because I think

00:08:22.442 --> 00:08:23.610
that really sets the framework.

00:08:23.610 --> 00:08:24.210
So I'm coming in.

00:08:24.210 --> 00:08:25.920
I told you about my
background, where I come from,

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:27.753
and what I was thinking
when I came to Duke.

00:08:27.753 --> 00:08:30.680
I was hoping I would be able to
come this cardiologist, someone

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:34.262
who's going to operate,
fix the heart, concrete.

00:08:34.262 --> 00:08:35.970
Everything-- that was
sort of my mindset.

00:08:35.970 --> 00:08:38.502
And then I got to Duke, and
something else happened.

00:08:38.502 --> 00:08:40.210
So let me just read
that introduction to.

00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:42.409
It will take about four
minutes, and then I'll

00:08:42.409 --> 00:08:44.690
discuss a little
more after that.

00:08:44.690 --> 00:08:48.940
"On a spring morning
in 1997, Jim Harper,

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:50.970
a young man from
Durham, North Carolina,

00:08:50.970 --> 00:08:53.220
woke up in his two bedroom
apartment with no clue

00:08:53.220 --> 00:08:55.660
that he would soon
become gravely ill.

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:58.850
The first signs of trouble
seemed innocent enough.

00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:01.480
Numbness on the right
side of his face and hand,

00:09:01.480 --> 00:09:04.660
easily chalked up to having
slept on that side of his body.

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:06.110
He stumbled as he
got out of bed,

00:09:06.110 --> 00:09:09.310
but figured he was simply tired
from the previous day's work.

00:09:09.310 --> 00:09:12.980
His fiancee, Regina, asked
if he needed to see a doctor.

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:15.920
He smiled and told her
that she worried too much.

00:09:15.920 --> 00:09:18.160
Her anxiety ebbed as
she went off to her job

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:21.460
at Kmart, only to resurface
when he didn't answer the phone

00:09:21.460 --> 00:09:23.344
during her lunch break.

00:09:23.344 --> 00:09:25.510
When Regina rushed home a
few hours later at the end

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:28.180
of her shift, she found Jim
sprawled across their bathroom

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:29.190
floor.

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:31.730
His eyes were wide open,
and he recognized her,

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:33.132
but his words were garbled.

00:09:33.132 --> 00:09:34.590
He couldn't tell
her what was wrong

00:09:34.590 --> 00:09:36.820
or how long he'd been that way.

00:09:36.820 --> 00:09:39.187
She frantically dialed 911.

00:09:39.187 --> 00:09:41.270
Within a half hour of his
arrival at the emergency

00:09:41.270 --> 00:09:45.380
department, after a neurological
exam and CAT scan of his brain,

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:47.410
it was clear what had happened.

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:51.675
Jim, just a few weeks shy of 40,
had suffered a massive stroke.

00:09:51.675 --> 00:09:54.050
The doctors learned that Jim
had high blood pressure that

00:09:54.050 --> 00:09:56.000
had been poorly treated,
but nothing else

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.790
to account for his tragic fate.

00:09:57.790 --> 00:10:01.570
He had no heart problems,
no aneurysms, no diabetes,

00:10:01.570 --> 00:10:02.820
or high cholesterol.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:06.930
he didn't smoke, really drank,
and avoided street drugs.

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:08.650
Ultimately, as best
they could tell,

00:10:08.650 --> 00:10:11.070
Jim mostly had a
lot of bad luck.

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:13.620
About two weeks later, I
stood at the foot of Jim's bed

00:10:13.620 --> 00:10:14.840
at Duke Hospital.

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:17.030
Along with another first
year medical student,

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:19.930
I was shadowing Dr.
Wilson, a neurologist,

00:10:19.930 --> 00:10:21.830
as part of a weekly
class that introduced us

00:10:21.830 --> 00:10:23.272
to clinical medicine.

00:10:23.272 --> 00:10:24.730
This was the
highlight of our week,

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:27.555
as it gave us a brief break from
the lecture hall and laboratory

00:10:27.555 --> 00:10:29.180
and provided a peek
at our future lives

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:30.980
on the hospital wards.

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:33.070
We wore perfectly
knotted ties--"

00:10:33.070 --> 00:10:35.630
as I've tried to today--
"and crisp white coats

00:10:35.630 --> 00:10:37.920
for the occasion, trying
hard to look like the doctors

00:10:37.920 --> 00:10:39.830
we would one day become.

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:42.230
But Jim's future seemed
far less promising.

00:10:42.230 --> 00:10:44.390
A big man, he'd once
been a football player.

00:10:44.390 --> 00:10:46.810
Now he could not move the
right side of his body.

00:10:46.810 --> 00:10:48.435
His face drooped as
saliva dribbled out

00:10:48.435 --> 00:10:50.490
of the corner of his mouth.

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:52.340
Given his lack of
improvement, the doctors

00:10:52.340 --> 00:10:54.780
had begun to doubt he
could make any recovery.

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:57.672
They were preparing to
send him to a facility.

00:10:57.672 --> 00:10:59.380
This place also had
a long-term care unit

00:10:59.380 --> 00:11:00.990
where if he made no
progress, he might

00:11:00.990 --> 00:11:03.280
spend the rest of his life.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:06.080
'It's a very sad case,' Dr.
Wilson said as we left the room

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:08.663
and walked to a conference area
to discuss our patient and his

00:11:08.663 --> 00:11:09.272
illness.

00:11:09.272 --> 00:11:11.480
He started by telling us
that stroke was consistently

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:14.450
one of the top causes of death
and disability in America.

00:11:14.450 --> 00:11:16.450
Then he drilled us about
the major risk factors,

00:11:16.450 --> 00:11:20.020
going back and forth between
us in a competition of sorts.

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:21.860
In eager medical
student fashion,

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:23.640
we routed off the
usual suspects.

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:28.140
Diabetes, high blood pressure,
heart disease, old age,

00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:30.786
smoking, and high cholesterol."

00:11:30.786 --> 00:11:32.780
I ran out of fingers there.

00:11:32.780 --> 00:11:34.699
"When it was my turn
again, Dr. Wilson

00:11:34.699 --> 00:11:36.490
indicated that there
was one important risk

00:11:36.490 --> 00:11:38.290
factor we had yet to mention.

00:11:38.290 --> 00:11:40.360
He looked at me with
a worried frown.

00:11:40.360 --> 00:11:41.480
Come on, his look said.

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:44.460
For you of all people,
this should be easy.

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:45.460
I sighed.

00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:47.220
I'd hoped it wouldn't
come to this,

00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:50.570
but as I was quickly
learning, it always did.

00:11:50.570 --> 00:11:53.120
'Race,' I said, looking
down at my dark hand against

00:11:53.120 --> 00:11:54.920
my pristine white coat.

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:58.420
'Our patient is black.'
'Exactly,' Dr. Wilson said,

00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:01.610
as if I'd now earned a
top score on my exam.

00:12:01.610 --> 00:12:05.160
Some would say that this is the
most important variable of all.

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:08.380
He routed off statistics
about race and stroke.

00:12:08.380 --> 00:12:10.420
The risk is twice as
high for blacks compared

00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:13.900
to whites for those over
65, and in younger groups,

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:15.650
such as our patient
here, the ratio

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:18.810
is more like three to
one, or even four to one.

00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:21.710
I'd seen the impact of stroke
on both sides of my family.

00:12:21.710 --> 00:12:24.670
When I was 14, my dad's
brother, who would often

00:12:24.670 --> 00:12:27.570
drive five hours each
way on a Saturday just

00:12:27.570 --> 00:12:29.600
to visit us for
a few hours, died

00:12:29.600 --> 00:12:31.660
within days of
collapsing at his home,

00:12:31.660 --> 00:12:34.860
putting an abrupt end to his
visits that I always enjoyed.

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:37.670
A few years later, my maternal
grandmother, Grandma Flossie,

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:40.630
developed dementia from
a series of minor strokes

00:12:40.630 --> 00:12:43.990
that slowly stole her mind
and eventually her body.

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:46.741
Like Jim, both had
high blood pressure.

00:12:46.741 --> 00:12:49.240
'Our patient's other major risk
factor is hypertension,' Dr.

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:50.570
Wilson continued.

00:12:50.570 --> 00:12:52.680
'This is also much more
prevalent in blacks.

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:54.382
Nearly twice as common.

00:12:54.382 --> 00:12:56.840
No matter how you slice it,
race is a very big deal when it

00:12:56.840 --> 00:13:00.720
comes to stroke.' Dr. Wilson had
hammered home something I would

00:13:00.720 --> 00:13:05.080
learn time and again,
both at Duke and beyond.

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:08.330
Being black can be
bad for your health."

00:13:08.330 --> 00:13:09.950
So that really
lays the framework.

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:12.290
So I'm coming to
medical school, feeling

00:13:12.290 --> 00:13:14.820
as if I'm escaping this world
and going into a world that's

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:16.380
objective and concrete.

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:19.872
And during that first year, I
was inundated by these messages

00:13:19.872 --> 00:13:21.830
that there was something
wrong with being black

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:22.870
in terms of health.

00:13:22.870 --> 00:13:24.930
So every time you learn
about a disease-- heart

00:13:24.930 --> 00:13:26.786
disease, diabetes,
cancer-- the professors

00:13:26.786 --> 00:13:28.410
would start with sort
of the biology it

00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:30.304
it, what they call
the pathophysiology

00:13:30.304 --> 00:13:30.970
of the disorder.

00:13:30.970 --> 00:13:32.719
And then they would
always kind of go back

00:13:32.719 --> 00:13:34.510
to the end, talk about
the demographics.

00:13:34.510 --> 00:13:35.750
Who does it affect?

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:37.660
And there were always
two statements.

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:39.450
It's more common
in black people,

00:13:39.450 --> 00:13:41.990
and black people who get
the disease do much worse.

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:44.690
So those were the
statement they would make.

00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:47.670
And so for me the next
question was, why?

00:13:47.670 --> 00:13:49.840
And what could be done about it?

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:51.240
And I never seemed
to get answers

00:13:51.240 --> 00:13:53.300
to either of those
questions during that time.

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:54.300
There were just sort
of these statements

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:55.370
that were made out there.

00:13:55.370 --> 00:14:00.467
And not only was it--
these statements-- not only

00:14:00.467 --> 00:14:02.300
was there, like, an
intellectual side to it,

00:14:02.300 --> 00:14:03.925
but there was this
personal side to it,

00:14:03.925 --> 00:14:06.470
because these are things that
affected me, my own family,

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:07.540
and my actually myself.

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:08.410
And I'll talk about more later.

00:14:08.410 --> 00:14:09.710
And so it had great meaning.

00:14:09.710 --> 00:14:11.290
So this is really one of the
two main goals of the book,

00:14:11.290 --> 00:14:12.700
to really explore
those questions.

00:14:12.700 --> 00:14:14.060
Like, what does all this
mean, and why are we

00:14:14.060 --> 00:14:14.770
in this situation?

00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:16.769
So that's one of the two
main goals of the book.

00:14:16.769 --> 00:14:18.250
And what I discovered
along the way

00:14:18.250 --> 00:14:20.230
as I started to go
out into the community

00:14:20.230 --> 00:14:22.480
and start to see patients
and get to see-- so I really

00:14:22.480 --> 00:14:24.438
saw that there were,
like, three different ways

00:14:24.438 --> 00:14:25.750
of looking at this problem.

00:14:25.750 --> 00:14:26.580
And I talk about
these in the book.

00:14:26.580 --> 00:14:29.038
And what I do is I use case
studies of people that actually

00:14:29.038 --> 00:14:31.120
saw in various settings
that illustrate

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:32.590
with these issues are.

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:34.810
So certainly there's an
issue at the big level,

00:14:34.810 --> 00:14:38.220
at the macro level, the
system level, society.

00:14:38.220 --> 00:14:41.155
Black people are much more
likely to be uninsured, much

00:14:41.155 --> 00:14:42.780
more likely to live
in communities that

00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:45.840
are segregated, less access
to medical care, primary care

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:46.340
specialists.

00:14:46.340 --> 00:14:48.097
All those things are very true.

00:14:48.097 --> 00:14:49.930
And this has all been
known for a long time.

00:14:49.930 --> 00:14:51.388
What I wanted to
do in the book was

00:14:51.388 --> 00:14:53.335
to sort of use
examples of real people

00:14:53.335 --> 00:14:56.110
to illustrate how this
plays out in real life.

00:14:56.110 --> 00:15:00.160
And so in medical school, we
one day volunteered at a clinic

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:01.830
about 90 minutes from campus.

00:15:01.830 --> 00:15:04.815
And this is a decent
part of North Carolina.

00:15:04.815 --> 00:15:07.580
The community's 50-50,
half white, half black.

00:15:07.580 --> 00:15:10.870
But in this clinic you go
to, everyone there is black.

00:15:10.870 --> 00:15:11.444
All black.

00:15:11.444 --> 00:15:12.860
And it's a charity
clinic, so it's

00:15:12.860 --> 00:15:15.160
a clinic for people who can't
afford other health care.

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:16.620
Patients don't have
health insurance.

00:15:16.620 --> 00:15:17.860
And it's pretty clear
when you get there

00:15:17.860 --> 00:15:20.070
that you're providing
care, a level of care that

00:15:20.070 --> 00:15:21.974
is in many ways substandard.

00:15:21.974 --> 00:15:23.640
Despite your best
efforts or intentions,

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:25.490
the patients can't
afford medications,

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:27.910
lab tests, all the usual things
that we take for granted.

00:15:27.910 --> 00:15:29.290
Even the site of
it is so different.

00:15:29.290 --> 00:15:31.081
You think about the
typical medical clinic.

00:15:31.081 --> 00:15:33.050
So this kind of clinic,
there's no nurse there,

00:15:33.050 --> 00:15:34.799
and students are taking
the blood pressure

00:15:34.799 --> 00:15:38.180
and doing everything that a
nurse would ordinarily do.

00:15:38.180 --> 00:15:39.220
It was a one room house.

00:15:39.220 --> 00:15:40.928
I mean, you're not
talking about anything

00:15:40.928 --> 00:15:43.670
that any of us most
likely are experiencing.

00:15:43.670 --> 00:15:47.300
And so that really illustrated
sort of the big issue problems

00:15:47.300 --> 00:15:49.234
in a sort of micro way.

00:15:49.234 --> 00:15:50.900
There was another
time a couple of years

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:52.890
later where I worked in an
inner city emergency room.

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:54.150
So it's sort of
the opposite end.

00:15:54.150 --> 00:15:55.525
That one was a
very rural clinic.

00:15:55.525 --> 00:15:58.030
This is an inner city emergency
room clinic down in Atlanta.

00:15:58.030 --> 00:16:01.170
And there, you saw many of
the same problems again.

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:04.430
Even though Atlanta, even
though the residents-- people

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:06.620
are living in what seems
like a metropolitan area,

00:16:06.620 --> 00:16:08.809
there are ways that they're
cut off from society.

00:16:08.809 --> 00:16:10.350
And it really came
home to me one day

00:16:10.350 --> 00:16:12.310
when we took an ambulance ride.

00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:13.830
I was riding with
the paramedics.

00:16:13.830 --> 00:16:16.760
And we got a call to go
out to this community.

00:16:16.760 --> 00:16:18.480
And it's like you
go off this road,

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:20.480
and you're there for,
like, five or ten minutes.

00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:21.730
It feels like you're
going into the woods,

00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:22.510
in the wilderness in a way.

00:16:22.510 --> 00:16:23.301
It's like a suburb.

00:16:23.301 --> 00:16:26.640
And then you come into
this really just gruesome,

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:28.090
horrible housing project.

00:16:28.090 --> 00:16:30.570
And you just see the
chaos, and you see

00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:32.150
how all that affects health.

00:16:32.150 --> 00:16:34.357
And so you see obesity,
violence, addiction.

00:16:34.357 --> 00:16:35.690
Everything's just there for you.

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:37.606
So it was a vivid
illustration, and I describe

00:16:37.606 --> 00:16:39.140
that scene in the book.

00:16:39.140 --> 00:16:41.056
I actually describe it
much better than I just

00:16:41.056 --> 00:16:42.430
explained to you in the book.

00:16:42.430 --> 00:16:44.910
But those are the system
level things that you see,

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:46.367
and how those influence health.

00:16:46.367 --> 00:16:48.950
But then the next layer to that
is the doctor and the patient,

00:16:48.950 --> 00:16:51.300
and how they get together,
how they get along or don't.

00:16:51.300 --> 00:16:54.340
And how issues like
trust and communication,

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:56.930
bias, all these things
impact health care.

00:16:56.930 --> 00:17:00.160
And so in this part of the
book, I use other examples.

00:17:00.160 --> 00:17:02.560
So there's one
example of a gentleman

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:07.512
that I mentioned where he comes
to a hospital with chest pain,

00:17:07.512 --> 00:17:08.970
and seems to have
medical problems,

00:17:08.970 --> 00:17:10.500
but winds up
leaving the hospital

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:13.589
with a psychiatric diagnosis,
which was really unusual.

00:17:13.589 --> 00:17:17.655
And the book really explores
how that happened in a real way.

00:17:17.655 --> 00:17:20.357
And so how what seemed
like a concrete issue

00:17:20.357 --> 00:17:21.940
became something
completely different.

00:17:21.940 --> 00:17:24.700
And I also talk about a
situation where I was a patient

00:17:24.700 --> 00:17:26.790
and had a similar
type of experience,

00:17:26.790 --> 00:17:30.180
where I went in one day to a
clinic dressed very casually,

00:17:30.180 --> 00:17:32.860
and I was perceived one way,
in a less than favorable way.

00:17:32.860 --> 00:17:35.890
And then once it was made
aware that I was a doctor,

00:17:35.890 --> 00:17:37.040
then everything changed.

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:39.350
Sort of like being two
different people at one time.

00:17:39.350 --> 00:17:40.500
So those are just
examples in the book

00:17:40.500 --> 00:17:42.291
of how these things
can play out and affect

00:17:42.291 --> 00:17:44.390
health care in real ways.

00:17:44.390 --> 00:17:46.085
Then there's this other piece.

00:17:46.085 --> 00:17:47.460
So we talked about
the system, we

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:48.440
talked about the
doctor and the patient.

00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:51.120
But then there's the person
themselves and what they do,

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:53.336
what they eat, all the
daily things of life

00:17:53.336 --> 00:17:54.710
and how that
affects your health.

00:17:54.710 --> 00:17:57.142
And so here in the book, I
use a couple of examples.

00:17:57.142 --> 00:17:59.600
There was one time where I saw
two different patients, very

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:03.300
similar backgrounds, but one was
able to make the kind of health

00:18:03.300 --> 00:18:05.439
choices that led
to a good outcome,

00:18:05.439 --> 00:18:06.480
and one was the opposite.

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:09.560
And I explore the reasons
why and ways in which

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:11.691
choices are influenced
by all sorts of things.

00:18:11.691 --> 00:18:13.690
Family, surroundings, all
those sorts of things.

00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:14.180
So I explore that.

00:18:14.180 --> 00:18:16.180
I also talk about it from
my own personal level.

00:18:18.382 --> 00:18:20.715
Early in medical school, I
was diagnosed with high blood

00:18:20.715 --> 00:18:21.392
pressure myself.

00:18:21.392 --> 00:18:23.850
And I'll talk a little bit more
about that towards the end.

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:27.530
But I really explore how things
that the individual does also

00:18:27.530 --> 00:18:29.030
obviously greatly
influences health.

00:18:29.030 --> 00:18:31.080
And how there are
cultural issues at work

00:18:31.080 --> 00:18:33.325
that sometimes,
for many reasons,

00:18:33.325 --> 00:18:35.450
can affect the health of
African Americans as well.

00:18:35.450 --> 00:18:36.700
So I explore all these issues.

00:18:36.700 --> 00:18:38.910
I sort of tackle everything
in this book in that way.

00:18:38.910 --> 00:18:40.410
So that's one big
piece of the book.

00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:42.570
Why is being black
bad for your health?

00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:44.264
The second big piece
of the book is,

00:18:44.264 --> 00:18:46.680
what is it like to be an African
American doctor, and what

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:47.840
is that experience like?

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:49.923
Because that's really the
second piece of the book

00:18:49.923 --> 00:18:50.920
that I talk about.

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:54.020
As I mentioned at the beginning,
African Americans are about 13%

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:56.381
of the population,
4% of doctors.

00:18:56.381 --> 00:18:58.630
It was very common-- so when
I went to medical school,

00:18:58.630 --> 00:19:00.680
I was in the first class
at Duke where they really

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:03.263
were increasing the numbers of
African Americans considerably.

00:19:03.263 --> 00:19:05.890
In previous years, there had
been much, much fewer numbers.

00:19:05.890 --> 00:19:09.100
And that raised a couple
of different issues.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:11.750
One was this issue about how
you perceive this perception.

00:19:11.750 --> 00:19:13.000
So you're an African American.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:14.850
You're sort of seen
as a rare thing,

00:19:14.850 --> 00:19:17.100
and sometimes people don't
know how to perceive you.

00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:20.374
And so there are
a couple examples

00:19:20.374 --> 00:19:21.540
I'll talk about it the book.

00:19:21.540 --> 00:19:23.748
One occurred when I was a
first year medical student.

00:19:23.748 --> 00:19:27.170
When I came into a
classroom, a professor

00:19:27.170 --> 00:19:28.670
approached me in a
sort of angry way

00:19:28.670 --> 00:19:31.700
and asked me to fix the
lights in the classroom,

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:33.940
and was under the mistaken
assumption that I was

00:19:33.940 --> 00:19:35.326
someone other than who I was.

00:19:35.326 --> 00:19:37.950
An so I talk about that incident
and kind of how it affected me

00:19:37.950 --> 00:19:40.075
because I was already kind
of insecure about coming

00:19:40.075 --> 00:19:40.990
into medical school.

00:19:40.990 --> 00:19:44.590
So I explore how I dealt
with that situation.

00:19:44.590 --> 00:19:46.980
There was another time a few
years later as a first year

00:19:46.980 --> 00:19:47.480
resident.

00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:50.470
So this when you finish medical
school, and your first year

00:19:50.470 --> 00:19:51.560
is called an intern.

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:52.759
That's when you like an MD.

00:19:52.759 --> 00:19:54.800
So you're technically an
MD, but you don't really

00:19:54.800 --> 00:19:56.215
feel like one because there's
so much responsibility

00:19:56.215 --> 00:19:57.714
and you're just
learning everything.

00:19:57.714 --> 00:19:59.830
And so it's a big
adjustment for every doctor.

00:19:59.830 --> 00:20:04.530
But about a month into that
first year, a patient, an older

00:20:04.530 --> 00:20:07.190
white gentleman came in
and one of the first words

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:10.471
out of his mouth was that he
did not want a black doctor.

00:20:10.471 --> 00:20:13.610
And he used a racial slur to
sort of express what he meant.

00:20:13.610 --> 00:20:17.032
And only it happened that I was
the only black doctor working

00:20:17.032 --> 00:20:19.240
in the hospital at that
time, which was not uncommon.

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:21.470
So it was sort of these
twist of fate or karma

00:20:21.470 --> 00:20:23.720
or whatever that he would
be assigned to the same team

00:20:23.720 --> 00:20:25.400
that I was at.

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:26.970
So that story actually
has a surprise

00:20:26.970 --> 00:20:29.780
ending that I won't
spoil for you here.

00:20:29.780 --> 00:20:31.280
But I'm just giving
examples of some

00:20:31.280 --> 00:20:32.905
of the different ways
of how perception

00:20:32.905 --> 00:20:35.040
is so important to my journey.

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:36.540
One of the issues
that also comes up

00:20:36.540 --> 00:20:39.460
with being a black doctor where
you're one of few black doctors

00:20:39.460 --> 00:20:41.790
and there's a large black
population around you

00:20:41.790 --> 00:20:44.027
is that there's this
sort of supply and demand

00:20:44.027 --> 00:20:44.610
kind of issue.

00:20:44.610 --> 00:20:47.140
So there are often many African
American patients-- not always,

00:20:47.140 --> 00:20:48.380
but there are many
who would like

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:49.921
to have an African
American provider,

00:20:49.921 --> 00:20:52.362
particularly in a field like
primary care or psychiatry,

00:20:52.362 --> 00:20:54.070
which in my field,
where the relationship

00:20:54.070 --> 00:20:56.855
with the doctor and the patient
is especially important.

00:20:56.855 --> 00:20:58.440
And so often there's
this issue that

00:20:58.440 --> 00:21:00.730
comes up where
there's large numbers

00:21:00.730 --> 00:21:04.059
of African American patients
and very few providers.

00:21:04.059 --> 00:21:05.600
So for instance in
Durham-- so Duke's

00:21:05.600 --> 00:21:06.683
in Durham, North Carolina.

00:21:06.683 --> 00:21:10.645
Populations about
45% African American.

00:21:10.645 --> 00:21:13.440
But you look at other medical
schools and hospitals.

00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:16.140
So Johns Hopkins is in
Baltimore, which is 60% black.

00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:21.370
And Atlanta-- in Philadelphia,
UPENN, is 50% black.

00:21:21.370 --> 00:21:23.475
Even in Boston where
it's like 25% black,

00:21:23.475 --> 00:21:25.100
something like that,
that's still about

00:21:25.100 --> 00:21:26.950
double the black
population nationwide

00:21:26.950 --> 00:21:28.002
which is like 12%, 13%.

00:21:28.002 --> 00:21:29.960
So even in a city like
Boston or New York where

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:30.990
the numbers are slightly lower.

00:21:30.990 --> 00:21:32.647
So you have this
dynamic of places

00:21:32.647 --> 00:21:35.230
where so many of the doctors or
medical students and residents

00:21:35.230 --> 00:21:36.980
are trained, being
in these communities

00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:38.800
where large African
American populations

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:40.300
and where there's
often historically

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:42.470
been this sort of tension
between the communities

00:21:42.470 --> 00:21:44.040
and these very sort of
wealthy institutions.

00:21:44.040 --> 00:21:46.480
So the book kind of explores
all those dynamics as well,

00:21:46.480 --> 00:21:49.630
and what that means for you.

00:21:49.630 --> 00:21:51.760
Finally, there's
this other piece.

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:53.449
Being a black
doctor, I come from,

00:21:53.449 --> 00:21:54.865
as I mentioned at
the beginning, I

00:21:54.865 --> 00:21:57.530
come from a very working class
African American community,

00:21:57.530 --> 00:21:58.680
segregated community.

00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:00.471
Many of the patients
that I saw reminded me

00:22:00.471 --> 00:22:01.840
of myself, my family.

00:22:01.840 --> 00:22:05.542
But then I'm becoming
part of this other system,

00:22:05.542 --> 00:22:08.736
this white coat and the
hierarchy of being a doctor.

00:22:08.736 --> 00:22:11.110
So black man in a white coat
is kind of like a symbolism.

00:22:11.110 --> 00:22:12.526
It's having two identities.

00:22:12.526 --> 00:22:14.150
You're navigating
those two identities.

00:22:14.150 --> 00:22:16.720
And so in times I would feel
as if-- many times I talk about

00:22:16.720 --> 00:22:18.852
in the book, I feel like
I had a foot in one world,

00:22:18.852 --> 00:22:20.310
this is the African
American world.

00:22:20.310 --> 00:22:21.518
Now I'm in the medical world.

00:22:21.518 --> 00:22:22.960
And so where do I fit in there?

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:24.419
And do I have a
foot in this world?

00:22:24.419 --> 00:22:25.876
And do I have a
foot in that world?

00:22:25.876 --> 00:22:28.490
Or do I have-- so it's like
trying to find your grounding.

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:30.270
People have written-- many
African American philosophers

00:22:30.270 --> 00:22:32.260
have written about this, a term
called double consciousness.

00:22:32.260 --> 00:22:33.610
I mean, there's all sorts
of ways of looking at it.

00:22:33.610 --> 00:22:35.090
But I explore it
from the context

00:22:35.090 --> 00:22:37.120
of being a doctor in
the medical system.

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:39.407
So that's another big
piece of the book as well.

00:22:39.407 --> 00:22:41.990
So finally the book talks about,
where does all this leave us?

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:44.420
So I've outlined all these
problems, these issues we have.

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:45.870
And so in the book, towards
the end of the book,

00:22:45.870 --> 00:22:46.610
I try and touch on that.

00:22:46.610 --> 00:22:48.050
Say, where do we go from here?

00:22:48.050 --> 00:22:50.620
And so when you go back
to what the problems are

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:52.555
at the level of
the system, there

00:22:52.555 --> 00:22:55.005
are all sorts of
problems of course.

00:22:55.005 --> 00:22:56.505
I talk about the
Affordable Care Act

00:22:56.505 --> 00:23:00.360
and kind of the pros and cons
of that, where that's left us.

00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:02.100
And so actually a
few years ago, I

00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:04.742
went back to some of the
clinics that I initially worked

00:23:04.742 --> 00:23:06.450
at as a medical student
and sort of tried

00:23:06.450 --> 00:23:08.430
to take stock of
where things had gone

00:23:08.430 --> 00:23:10.740
and had the Affordable
Care Act helped?

00:23:10.740 --> 00:23:12.440
And, you know, it's
a mixed picture

00:23:12.440 --> 00:23:13.945
because it's so politicized.

00:23:13.945 --> 00:23:15.440
It's been so politicized.

00:23:15.440 --> 00:23:17.505
Many states haven't
enacted certain provisions

00:23:17.505 --> 00:23:18.630
of the Affordable Care Act.

00:23:18.630 --> 00:23:19.838
North Carolina's one of them.

00:23:19.838 --> 00:23:23.360
And that's impact sort of
the real world effect of it.

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:26.136
But as a doctor, I understand
we have politics and people

00:23:26.136 --> 00:23:27.260
are bitter and contentious.

00:23:27.260 --> 00:23:28.890
But as a doctor, it's hard
to sometimes understand

00:23:28.890 --> 00:23:30.264
that because you've
seen patients

00:23:30.264 --> 00:23:32.559
from all political
backgrounds, all the time, who

00:23:32.559 --> 00:23:34.350
all have the same kinds
of health problems,

00:23:34.350 --> 00:23:35.430
get sick in the same way.

00:23:35.430 --> 00:23:37.940
And so you just wonder
as a doctor, why

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:40.010
it's so difficult
for us to have this--

00:23:40.010 --> 00:23:42.310
why has health care become
such a partisan issue?

00:23:42.310 --> 00:23:43.400
That's the doctor hat.

00:23:43.400 --> 00:23:44.500
I mean, the other
side of me knows why.

00:23:44.500 --> 00:23:46.890
But it's such a frustrating
thing to see as a doctor,

00:23:46.890 --> 00:23:49.320
and I explore that as well.

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:52.941
Another piece of it
at the macro level

00:23:52.941 --> 00:23:54.940
is, how do we get more
African American doctors?

00:23:54.940 --> 00:23:56.100
What can we do about that?

00:23:56.100 --> 00:23:57.599
And one of the more
troubling things

00:23:57.599 --> 00:24:00.710
is that African American--
the numbers of doctors

00:24:00.710 --> 00:24:02.610
have increased across
the board pretty much

00:24:02.610 --> 00:24:03.570
over the last 30 years.

00:24:03.570 --> 00:24:05.028
The population
[INAUDIBLE] growing,

00:24:05.028 --> 00:24:07.050
and the number of doctors
have grown with it.

00:24:07.050 --> 00:24:09.510
And that's true in all groups
of people with the exception

00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:10.510
of African American men.

00:24:10.510 --> 00:24:13.000
So African American women and
medical students and doctors

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.375
have probably doubled
since the late 1970s.

00:24:15.375 --> 00:24:18.000
But African American men, their
numbers are actually flatlined.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.250
In some place, even slightly
declined since the late 1970s.

00:24:21.250 --> 00:24:23.920
And that's completely different
than every other group--

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:26.349
demographic in America.

00:24:26.349 --> 00:24:27.890
So that plays out
for me in many ways

00:24:27.890 --> 00:24:30.664
where I feel like I'm the only
person people are wanting--

00:24:30.664 --> 00:24:33.080
so you feel this sort of, like,
what is my responsibility?

00:24:33.080 --> 00:24:35.070
Where do I fit in as an
African American male?

00:24:35.070 --> 00:24:35.850
What can I do about that?

00:24:35.850 --> 00:24:38.266
So I explore all those kind
of issues in the book as well.

00:24:38.266 --> 00:24:41.030
And not just me, but what can
we do as a society as well?

00:24:41.030 --> 00:24:42.488
There's also this
piece in the book

00:24:42.488 --> 00:24:45.260
where I talk about-- I think
it's a really important piece.

00:24:45.260 --> 00:24:48.195
Because we have
few black doctors,

00:24:48.195 --> 00:24:49.570
most black patients
are not going

00:24:49.570 --> 00:24:50.986
to see an African
American doctor.

00:24:50.986 --> 00:24:53.502
And so there's this
whole idea about how

00:24:53.502 --> 00:24:54.960
do we sort of get
along with people

00:24:54.960 --> 00:24:55.890
who are very different from us?

00:24:55.890 --> 00:24:57.431
And so in the book
I talk about this.

00:24:57.431 --> 00:24:59.400
I talk a lot about the
white patients I see,

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:01.880
because about half of the
people I see are white.

00:25:01.880 --> 00:25:05.106
And how do we make
connections with people

00:25:05.106 --> 00:25:07.105
that we seem at first to
be very different from?

00:25:07.105 --> 00:25:08.760
And so that's a really
important piece of the book.

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:10.070
And I give a couple
examples of patients

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:12.290
where things were just so
completely different at first.

00:25:12.290 --> 00:25:14.070
You would never imagine that
we could have worked together.

00:25:14.070 --> 00:25:16.160
I mean, they had perceptions,
biases against me,

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:17.620
I had biases against them.

00:25:17.620 --> 00:25:20.150
We all carry these things.

00:25:20.150 --> 00:25:22.206
But I give examples of
how we're able to work

00:25:22.206 --> 00:25:23.080
through those things.

00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:25.080
And I'd like for that to
be a lesson or inspiration

00:25:25.080 --> 00:25:25.790
to other doctors.

00:25:25.790 --> 00:25:26.970
You know, white
doctors, Asian doctors,

00:25:26.970 --> 00:25:29.120
for how you can connect with
African American patients

00:25:29.120 --> 00:25:30.390
from whom you may
have completely

00:25:30.390 --> 00:25:31.306
different backgrounds.

00:25:31.306 --> 00:25:34.025
And so again, I'm using these
stories of my encounters

00:25:34.025 --> 00:25:35.824
with people to sort
of try and illuminate

00:25:35.824 --> 00:25:37.115
larger problems in our society.

00:25:37.115 --> 00:25:40.020
So that's really where I'm
coming from in the book.

00:25:40.020 --> 00:25:41.530
And really, I think that's it.

00:25:41.530 --> 00:25:42.400
I think the really
important piece

00:25:42.400 --> 00:25:44.690
I want to get about this--
because what I'm learning along

00:25:44.690 --> 00:25:46.731
the way in writing this
book and getting feedback

00:25:46.731 --> 00:25:48.694
is how little people
know about these issues.

00:25:48.694 --> 00:25:50.110
So I really want
to educate people

00:25:50.110 --> 00:25:51.680
and just make-- the
awareness is so key.

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:52.930
I mean, we always hear
about, again, race

00:25:52.930 --> 00:25:55.007
through this lens of
criminal justice and crime

00:25:55.007 --> 00:25:56.090
and those sorts of issues.

00:25:56.090 --> 00:25:58.339
But it's a really huge deal
in the health care sector.

00:25:58.339 --> 00:26:00.672
Really in the long run, that
affects even more of us.

00:26:00.672 --> 00:26:01.630
That affects all of us.

00:26:01.630 --> 00:26:04.680
And so I really wanted to really
get people aware of this issue,

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:07.361
and hopefully inspire them
to inspire health systems.

00:26:07.361 --> 00:26:09.860
Because I've been talking to
medical schools and health care

00:26:09.860 --> 00:26:12.390
systems, inspiring doctors
and patients, all of us

00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:15.630
to do better and do our part
to really address this problem.

00:26:15.630 --> 00:26:18.130
So that's really my
perspective on this issue,

00:26:18.130 --> 00:26:19.620
and that's really my story.

00:26:19.620 --> 00:26:22.094
So thank you for your time.

00:26:22.094 --> 00:26:25.046
[APPLAUSE]

00:26:26.974 --> 00:26:28.140
I'm happy to take questions.

00:26:28.140 --> 00:26:30.150
Actually, I often like
the question part better.

00:26:30.150 --> 00:26:31.870
Kind of engage
with the audience,

00:26:31.870 --> 00:26:33.960
see what people have to say.

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:35.210
So thanks for bearing with me.

00:26:35.210 --> 00:26:36.503
