use of primary care at all,

00:27:55.990 --> 00:27:57.000
and so forth.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:58.990
I'm wondering, how
much of this problem

00:27:58.990 --> 00:28:03.330
is that the supply of primary
care has not improved?

00:28:03.330 --> 00:28:05.640
And the incentives
for doctors to go

00:28:05.640 --> 00:28:09.810
into primary care versus
specialties has not improved.

00:28:09.810 --> 00:28:13.470
Do we actually have any signs
that we're making progress

00:28:13.470 --> 00:28:16.760
in expanding primary
care and preventive

00:28:16.760 --> 00:28:18.610
care in those communities?

00:28:18.610 --> 00:28:20.130
And how much of
this is a problem

00:28:20.130 --> 00:28:22.030
that maybe there
is more of that,

00:28:22.030 --> 00:28:26.720
but people have habits
formed from long years,

00:28:26.720 --> 00:28:28.580
and they maybe
don't know about it

00:28:28.580 --> 00:28:32.060
or they're just used to
going to emergency rooms?

00:28:32.060 --> 00:28:35.470
How much of it is sort
of educational problems

00:28:35.470 --> 00:28:39.520
and getting that
population to think more

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:43.150
about getting primary care
that may be available to them?

00:28:43.150 --> 00:28:46.655
What are the real problems here,
and what do we do about it?

00:28:46.655 --> 00:28:48.780
DAMON TWEEDY: Yeah, I think
you touched on really--

00:28:48.780 --> 00:28:50.190
