00:29:36.367 --> 00:29:38.700
or like the ones here at
Harvard where the goal is often

00:29:38.700 --> 00:29:41.180
to train specialists
and researchers.

00:29:41.180 --> 00:29:44.310
But Duke has established
a primary care

00:29:44.310 --> 00:29:45.720
track for medical students.

00:29:45.720 --> 00:29:47.511
This has happened in
the last three or four

00:29:47.511 --> 00:29:50.830
years where they are basically
paying for their medical school

00:29:50.830 --> 00:29:53.260
tuition, which is
considerable, for students who

00:29:53.260 --> 00:29:55.960
agree to go into primary care
and practice primary care

00:29:55.960 --> 00:29:56.880
after medical school.

00:29:56.880 --> 00:29:58.490
And not only do that,
but there's also

00:29:58.490 --> 00:30:00.656
like a-- even their education
is somewhat different.

00:30:00.656 --> 00:30:03.337
It's really geared more towards
this idea of continuity of care

00:30:03.337 --> 00:30:05.795
and not just this sort of like--
normally in medical school

00:30:05.795 --> 00:30:07.955
you're taught in a hospital
setting where it's urgent

00:30:07.955 --> 00:30:08.510
and it's acute.

00:30:08.510 --> 00:30:10.370
And so they're really trying to
build relationships with people

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:11.560
and follow them over
time, which is really

00:30:11.560 --> 00:30:12.880
the purpose of primary care.

00:30:12.880 --> 00:30:14.170
So there are school-- many
schools are doing that,

00:30:14.170 --> 00:30:14.670
actually.

00:30:14.670 --> 00:30:16.360
I think Harvard has
a primary care track

00:30:16.360 --> 00:30:17.526
as well that they've set up.

00:30:17.526 --> 00:30:19.667
So many schools are
trying to do that.

00:30:19.667 --> 00:30:21.000
We're still in the early stages.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.770
So to see what the long-term
effects of that's going to be

00:30:23.770 --> 00:30:25.245
is still kind of unclear.

00:30:25.245 --> 00:30:26.370
So that's one aspect to it.

00:30:26.370 --> 00:30:28.078
So I think they are
trying to address it.

00:30:28.078 --> 00:30:30.460
It's clearly a problem
because of the reasons

00:30:30.460 --> 00:30:31.860
that we just talked about.

00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:34.060
The other issue-- I just
lose my train of-- you

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:35.450
asked so my
questions, I'm trying

00:30:35.450 --> 00:30:37.812
to make sure I've
addressed all of them.

00:30:37.812 --> 00:30:39.020
Gosh, what was the other one?

00:30:39.020 --> 00:30:39.930
Oh, yeah, about the communities.

00:30:39.930 --> 00:30:41.259
And so the patterns of care.

00:30:41.259 --> 00:30:41.800
You're right.

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:43.341
So African Americans
are so much more

00:30:43.341 --> 00:30:46.754
likely to be seen in urgent
care clinics, emergency room

00:30:46.754 --> 00:30:48.920
settings for what could be
managed in a primary care

00:30:48.920 --> 00:30:49.130
setting.

00:30:49.130 --> 00:30:50.713
There is a sort of
this pattern there.

00:30:50.713 --> 00:30:52.371
There's no doubt about that.

00:30:52.371 --> 00:30:53.370
Here's one road to that.

00:30:53.370 --> 00:30:56.320
One is that depending on
the kind of job you have,

00:30:56.320 --> 00:31:00.240
trying to go to see a
doctor requires sick leave.

00:31:00.240 --> 00:31:02.090
Some jobs don't have that.

00:31:02.090 --> 00:31:04.757
And I've had patients
where they get sick,

00:31:04.757 --> 00:31:06.340
they miss a few days
of work, and then

00:31:06.340 --> 00:31:07.550
they can lose their job.

00:31:07.550 --> 00:31:10.089
And so it's so
harsh in that way.

00:31:10.089 --> 00:31:11.880
Urgent care clinics,
emergency room clinics

00:31:11.880 --> 00:31:13.792
are always open after
hours, after work.

00:31:13.792 --> 00:31:16.250
So that's one way that it's
kind of been built up that way.

00:31:16.250 --> 00:31:18.121
That's one barrier,
for instance.

00:31:18.121 --> 00:31:19.620
So I think some
primary care clinics

00:31:19.620 --> 00:31:22.074
have tried to set up more
flexible hours and sort

00:31:22.074 --> 00:31:22.990
of accommodate people.

00:31:22.990 --> 00:31:24.250
But then there's also a
pattern, like you said.

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:26.360
You get used to doing
things a certain way.

00:31:26.360 --> 00:31:27.420
It's hard to break that.

00:31:27.420 --> 00:31:30.430
And it's really unfortunate
because I think--

00:31:30.430 --> 00:31:32.901
one of the things is when
you're seeing a doctor,

00:31:32.901 --> 00:31:34.900
you don't know that doctor,
they don't know you,

00:31:34.900 --> 00:31:36.983
it's much more likely to
get this impersonal care.

00:31:36.983 --> 00:31:38.310
They're less invested in you.

00:31:38.310 --> 00:31:39.440
And you're more
likely to have things

00:31:39.440 --> 00:31:41.190
like bias and other
things sort of intrude

00:31:41.190 --> 00:31:42.760
in the doctor-patient
relationship.

00:31:42.760 --> 00:31:44.045
So it's a big problem.

00:31:44.045 --> 00:31:46.755
So I think you really outlined
all the problems in many ways.

00:31:46.755 --> 00:31:48.697
I hope I addressed--
I think we're trying

00:31:48.697 --> 00:31:49.780
to address these problems.

00:31:49.780 --> 00:31:50.863
But they're huge problems.

00:31:50.863 --> 00:31:52.810
Huge problems to deal with.

00:31:52.810 --> 00:31:54.863
The piece about the
African American men

00:31:54.863 --> 00:31:56.362
and in society and
doctors-- I think

00:31:56.362 --> 00:31:57.750
that was the question
you were mentioning.

00:31:57.750 --> 00:31:59.910
Yeah, I mean, it's troubling
on a lot of levels.

00:31:59.910 --> 00:32:01.580
I mean, so for me,
one of the things

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:03.080
that when I was the
first thinking I

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:05.270
could become a
doctor, there still

00:32:05.270 --> 00:32:06.820
were very few role models.

00:32:06.820 --> 00:32:10.604
But I did a research lab-- got a
research position in the summer

00:32:10.604 --> 00:32:13.020
at the National Institute of
Health, which is in Maryland.

00:32:13.020 --> 00:32:14.811
And I met an African
American cardiologist.

00:32:14.811 --> 00:32:16.790
And so the idea of
seeing someone who looked

00:32:16.790 --> 00:32:18.920
like me and had gone that
route, it was tremendous.

00:32:18.920 --> 00:32:21.392
I mean, so it was
tremendously important to me.

00:32:21.392 --> 00:32:23.850
And I think that all too often
as an African American man--

00:32:23.850 --> 00:32:26.870
I can speak to this growing up--
the perceptions of what you can

00:32:26.870 --> 00:32:29.391
do and what you can accomplish
are so narrow and limited

00:32:29.391 --> 00:32:29.890
[INAUDIBLE].

00:32:29.890 --> 00:32:32.350
And I think I feel like it
comes from the top of society

00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:33.650
and it kind of filters
all the way down

00:32:33.650 --> 00:32:34.560
to the community where you live.

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:36.880
And I think that really just
narrows what you can do.

00:32:36.880 --> 00:32:38.630
I think there was a
kid in my neighborhood

00:32:38.630 --> 00:32:41.170
who was-- I thought he
was smarter than me,

00:32:41.170 --> 00:32:43.017
but he sort of kind of
fell into that thing

00:32:43.017 --> 00:32:44.850
about you can only do
certain-- there's only

00:32:44.850 --> 00:32:46.225
a certain narrow
road to success.

00:32:46.225 --> 00:32:49.450
And I feel like that really
limited what he ultimately

00:32:49.450 --> 00:32:49.950
achieved.

00:32:49.950 --> 00:32:52.070
And so I think that's
a huge problem.

00:32:52.070 --> 00:32:54.290
And so I think we can't
have enough visible

00:32:54.290 --> 00:32:56.650
African Americans who
are male who are just

00:32:56.650 --> 00:32:59.140
succeeding in other ways.

00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:01.154
And so I feel this
real responsibility

00:33:01.154 --> 00:33:02.570
to try and be
someone [INAUDIBLE].

00:33:02.570 --> 00:33:04.486
Even though that goes
against my personality--

00:33:04.486 --> 00:33:06.894
my personality is really
naturally very introverted

00:33:06.894 --> 00:33:07.810
and keeping to myself.

00:33:07.810 --> 00:33:10.594
But it really feels like
it's such an important issue.

00:33:10.594 --> 00:33:12.760
And the influence is so
great to be able to do that.

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:16.250
So that's my answer
to that question.

00:33:16.250 --> 00:33:19.686
I'll try and shorten my answers
so people can ask questions.

00:33:19.686 --> 00:33:21.470
[LAUGH]

00:33:21.470 --> 00:33:23.860
But that's such an issue of
passion for me, those issues.

00:33:26.530 --> 00:33:30.042
AUDIENCE: There's
another barrier, which

00:33:30.042 --> 00:33:31.500
I don't think I
have heard mention,

00:33:31.500 --> 00:33:33.730
but it's just it's
something that I've observed

00:33:33.730 --> 00:33:35.740
through personal experience.

00:33:35.740 --> 00:33:40.210
So I have a son who is just--
he's a freshman at college.

00:33:40.210 --> 00:33:42.260
He's been at college
about two weeks.

00:33:42.260 --> 00:33:47.130
I also have the
privilege of my godson,

00:33:47.130 --> 00:33:49.160
who is African American.

00:33:49.160 --> 00:33:54.070
And wonderful, bright,
nice young man.

00:33:54.070 --> 00:33:56.760
And he started school last year.

00:33:56.760 --> 00:34:03.470
He's at Mass College-- MCPHS in
Boston for pharmacy and health

00:34:03.470 --> 00:34:04.620
services, I think.

00:34:04.620 --> 00:34:06.790
And he's in a physician's
assistant program.

00:34:06.790 --> 00:34:08.719
It's a six-year program.

00:34:08.719 --> 00:34:15.880
So his single mom, low
income, but they've

00:34:15.880 --> 00:34:17.389
just worked so hard.

00:34:17.389 --> 00:34:24.530
Now his first semester, he went
full scholarship, full ride.

00:34:24.530 --> 00:34:25.030
Great.

00:34:25.030 --> 00:34:25.530
Wonderful.

00:34:25.530 --> 00:34:26.530
Wonderful privilege.

00:34:26.530 --> 00:34:29.800
His first semester,
he didn't do well.

00:34:29.800 --> 00:34:33.400
And second semester,
he worked really hard,

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:37.810
brought his grades up, used
tutoring and all of that.

00:34:37.810 --> 00:34:40.940
Couldn't bring his average up
enough to keep the scholarship.

00:34:40.940 --> 00:34:44.139
So now he's going back,
loans and all of that.

00:34:44.139 --> 00:34:51.290
Now my son's going in, and just
for me being in college myself

00:34:51.290 --> 00:34:53.190
and other parents
and all that, I

00:34:53.190 --> 00:34:58.260
know that freshman often
tank the first semester.

00:34:58.260 --> 00:34:58.969
It's a big shift.

00:34:58.969 --> 00:35:00.176
DAMON TWEEDY: Big adjustment.

00:35:00.176 --> 00:35:01.610
AUDIENCE: It's a
huge adjustment.

00:35:01.610 --> 00:35:05.350
But people with resources,
they think, well, OK.

00:35:05.350 --> 00:35:10.670
You got Cs, get
up there, please.

00:35:10.670 --> 00:35:14.389
When I went to MIT, they'd
actually recognize this,

00:35:14.389 --> 00:35:16.430
and they have this thing
for all the freshman are

00:35:16.430 --> 00:35:20.170
pass fail the first year
because they know about that.

00:35:20.170 --> 00:35:25.740
And I look at my godson, and
it feels like it's not fair.

00:35:25.740 --> 00:35:30.760
Like, people with low resources
who are depending on those

00:35:30.760 --> 00:35:33.827
scholarships, they
have no margin.

00:35:33.827 --> 00:35:34.660
They have no margin.

00:35:34.660 --> 00:35:36.200
He comes in and it's like, whoa.

00:35:36.200 --> 00:35:38.380
This is harder than I thought.

00:35:38.380 --> 00:35:42.290
And also, I've read-- I don't
know if this is-- you tell me

00:35:42.290 --> 00:35:43.754
if you agree with this or not.

00:35:43.754 --> 00:35:45.170
I read somewhere,
because I'm very

00:35:45.170 --> 00:35:49.160
interesting in this whole
topic, that they looked

00:35:49.160 --> 00:35:52.184
at people who were white,
people who were Asian,

00:35:52.184 --> 00:35:53.600
people who were
African Americans.

00:35:53.600 --> 00:35:55.890
And people who are African
American, I've read,

00:35:55.890 --> 00:36:00.240
are less willing to go
out and ask for help,

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:03.110
ask for tutoring
resources, than average.

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:05.210
Asian Americans tend
to be more willing.

00:36:05.210 --> 00:36:06.580
And it's a cultural thing.

00:36:06.580 --> 00:36:08.350
And so he didn't ask.

00:36:08.350 --> 00:36:10.350
This semester he asked
because his mom was like,

00:36:10.350 --> 00:36:11.724
you're talking to
the tutors, OK?

00:36:14.100 --> 00:36:19.090
And so that also, I'm
sure, affected his grade.

00:36:19.090 --> 00:36:22.340
And this is a good kid,
but he's now kind of--

00:36:22.340 --> 00:36:25.110
DAMON TWEEDY: Struggling more.

00:36:25.110 --> 00:36:27.804
AUDIENCE: --is now in a
more challenging place

00:36:27.804 --> 00:36:29.220
than he might have
been otherwise.

00:36:29.220 --> 00:36:29.760
DAMON TWEEDY: Yeah, sure.

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:30.259
So, yeah.

00:36:30.259 --> 00:36:32.780
I would the margin
of error is thinner.

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:34.760
I would definitely agree
with you in that part.

00:36:34.760 --> 00:36:35.290
And that is true.

00:36:35.290 --> 00:36:37.820
I think there's also-- because
when I started medical school,

00:36:37.820 --> 00:36:39.040
there's always this
sort of like-- well,

00:36:39.040 --> 00:36:41.248
there's this whole perception
for affirmative action.

00:36:41.248 --> 00:36:43.890
You got in and you're taking
spots from other people.

00:36:43.890 --> 00:36:45.505
And so you come--
it affects you.

00:36:45.505 --> 00:36:46.850
You hear people tell you this.

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:49.349
And you go in, and you wonder
if you're going to measure up.

00:36:49.349 --> 00:36:51.590
And so the first times
that you don't measure up,

00:36:51.590 --> 00:36:54.466
it really-- I mean,
you don't want

00:36:54.466 --> 00:36:55.840
to ask for help
because it's sort

00:36:55.840 --> 00:36:58.115
of fulfilling this perception
people already have of you

00:36:58.115 --> 00:36:59.760
that you can't make it,
and so you're even less

00:36:59.760 --> 00:37:01.660
likely to seek help because
you don't want to admit

00:37:01.660 --> 00:37:02.930
that you might have a problem.

00:37:02.930 --> 00:37:04.290
So it's a huge problem.

00:37:04.290 --> 00:37:06.990
And so I think
several schools have

00:37:06.990 --> 00:37:10.030
tried to be more aggressive
with being aware of that

00:37:10.030 --> 00:37:12.520
and trying to be more aggressive
with trying to establish

00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:14.670
support for students
in those backgrounds

00:37:14.670 --> 00:37:15.950
from the very beginning.

00:37:15.950 --> 00:37:19.020
So for instance, in college,
I attended a state college

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:20.310
at the University of Maryland.

00:37:20.310 --> 00:37:23.414
And we had a summer
program which

00:37:23.414 --> 00:37:25.580
really helped with that
sort of acclimation process.

00:37:25.580 --> 00:37:27.475
We got you familiar with the
counselors and the people who

00:37:27.475 --> 00:37:29.080
could help you if
you needed help.

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:30.210
So I think that's
a huge problem,

00:37:30.210 --> 00:37:32.626
and all too often, African
American students in particular

00:37:32.626 --> 00:37:35.030
are the ones who sort of
bear the brunt of that.

00:37:35.030 --> 00:37:37.160
So your story's one
I've heard many times

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:38.582
and can definitely relate to.

00:37:38.582 --> 00:37:39.790
So we're trying to do better.

00:37:39.790 --> 00:37:42.220
And I'm part of
a program at Duke

00:37:42.220 --> 00:37:45.196
where we try and reach to people
who are younger and trying

00:37:45.196 --> 00:37:47.320
to help them get through
this process, particularly

00:37:47.320 --> 00:37:48.861
African American
men, because there's

00:37:48.861 --> 00:37:51.545
such a huge problem
that's seen all over.

00:37:51.545 --> 00:37:52.130
So absolutely.

00:37:52.130 --> 00:37:54.087
That's a great question.

00:37:54.087 --> 00:37:54.920
Any other questions?

00:37:54.920 --> 00:37:55.711
Any other thoughts?

00:37:55.711 --> 00:37:58.096
Anyone have any ideas?

00:37:58.096 --> 00:37:59.070
Yeah.

00:37:59.070 --> 00:38:00.540
I'm an open book here.

00:38:00.540 --> 00:38:01.967
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:01.967 --> 00:38:03.425
AUDIENCE: It's OK
if you don't have

00:38:03.425 --> 00:38:04.591
an answer for this question.

00:38:04.591 --> 00:38:06.860
But I was wondering if
there's any ways you

00:38:06.860 --> 00:38:12.190
think that we can help as
pretty much white people not

00:38:12.190 --> 00:38:13.350
in medicine.

00:38:13.350 --> 00:38:14.640
What can we do to help?

00:38:14.640 --> 00:38:17.050
Because I think a lot of
us care about these kinds

00:38:17.050 --> 00:38:19.460
of inequalities, and we'd
like to help solve them.

00:38:19.460 --> 00:38:20.920
DAMON TWEEDY: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:38:20.920 --> 00:38:21.961
People ask that question.

00:38:21.961 --> 00:38:26.665
So what can you-- but the thing
is, people often underestimate.

00:38:26.665 --> 00:38:28.670
I mean, there's so much
happening in the world.

00:38:28.670 --> 00:38:29.640
Problems are so big.

00:38:29.640 --> 00:38:30.940
You often feel like
you're just helpless.

00:38:30.940 --> 00:38:33.240
There's nothing you can do
versus all these problems.

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:35.750
But never underestimate what
you can do as an individual

00:38:35.750 --> 00:38:37.700
to really improve
someone's life.

00:38:37.700 --> 00:38:39.311
I still go back to that teacher.

00:38:39.311 --> 00:38:41.060
She took time out of
her day to say, well,

00:38:41.060 --> 00:38:42.837
you really should try
and take this test.

00:38:42.837 --> 00:38:45.170
And she had to encourage me,
and I didn't want to do it.

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:46.500
I was really thinking
there was no way I'm

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:47.120
going to be able to do this.

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:49.300
And so for her to sort
of push me along that way

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:50.770
and to get me on
this path, I mean,

00:38:50.770 --> 00:38:52.311
she really helped
get me on the path.

00:38:52.311 --> 00:38:54.310
This was a 45-year-old
white woman, you know?

00:38:54.310 --> 00:38:58.370
And so just her
encouragement really

00:38:58.370 --> 00:38:59.620
changed my life in many ways.

00:38:59.620 --> 00:39:01.390
I mean, something like that.

00:39:01.390 --> 00:39:05.110
I think all too often it's
easy to get discouraged and be

00:39:05.110 --> 00:39:05.610
cynical.

00:39:05.610 --> 00:39:06.730
But I think that you
really underestimate

00:39:06.730 --> 00:39:07.660
the power you can have.

00:39:07.660 --> 00:39:09.500
So she helped me, and now
I'm in the position where I

00:39:09.500 --> 00:39:10.970
can help so many other people.

00:39:10.970 --> 00:39:12.636
And I think it sort
of builds like that.

00:39:12.636 --> 00:39:14.887
And so I think that's what
I would tell people who are

00:39:14.887 --> 00:39:16.094
in a position to help people.

00:39:16.094 --> 00:39:17.960
Because I mean, all
you folks here and just

00:39:17.960 --> 00:39:19.534
going to help people
in your own way

00:39:19.534 --> 00:39:21.200
even if you can't fix
the whole problem.

00:39:21.200 --> 00:39:23.300
Because so much of health
is about these issues

00:39:23.300 --> 00:39:24.400
that aren't just strictly
about health care

00:39:24.400 --> 00:39:24.940
and the medical treatment.

00:39:24.940 --> 00:39:26.670
You don't have to be a doctor
to really improve health.

00:39:26.670 --> 00:39:29.230
If you can improve people's
educational opportunities, job

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:31.040
opportunities, you're
totally transforming

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:33.350
people's lives in ways
that you may not realize.

00:39:33.350 --> 00:39:35.225
And you're not only
transforming their lives.

00:39:35.225 --> 00:39:37.141
You're transforming their
health, potentially.

00:39:37.141 --> 00:39:40.840
So just think about that as you
sort of go out into the world.

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:43.020
That's what I would
say to your question.

00:39:43.020 --> 00:39:46.074
Never underestimate what
you can do in that way.

00:39:46.074 --> 00:39:47.010
Yeah.

00:39:47.010 --> 00:39:48.946
Yes sir?

00:39:48.946 --> 00:39:50.320
AUDIENCE: Have
you looked at some

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:52.120
of the stats in
the nursing field,

00:39:52.120 --> 00:39:55.590
and seeing how those kind
of differ or match up

00:39:55.590 --> 00:39:58.390
to some of the percentages that
you mentioned with physicians?

00:39:58.390 --> 00:40:00.150
DAMON TWEEDY: Great question.

00:40:00.150 --> 00:40:01.421
That's a good question.

00:40:01.421 --> 00:40:02.420
So I'm in mental health.

00:40:02.420 --> 00:40:07.410
And so I've looked actually
at-- so mental health field,

00:40:07.410 --> 00:40:08.980
there's psychiatrists
and there's

00:40:08.980 --> 00:40:10.640
psychologists and
family therapists

00:40:10.640 --> 00:40:11.598
and all sort of things.

00:40:11.598 --> 00:40:13.460
So the numbers are
really even lower.

00:40:13.460 --> 00:40:15.980
So actually, even lower
than they are in medicine.

00:40:15.980 --> 00:40:18.260
That's also the case if
you're looking at stats for,

00:40:18.260 --> 00:40:20.142
like-- I'm trying to
think about nursing.

00:40:20.142 --> 00:40:22.600
I put the nurse practitioners--
the nurse practitioners are

00:40:22.600 --> 00:40:24.433
sort of like a similar--
the specialist kind

00:40:24.433 --> 00:40:25.850
of advanced practiced nurse.

00:40:25.850 --> 00:40:27.470
The numbers there
are actually lower

00:40:27.470 --> 00:40:28.678
than they are for physicians.

00:40:28.678 --> 00:40:30.940
So the number's,
like, less than 5%.

00:40:30.940 --> 00:40:33.250
So I think that's
pretty much across-- so

00:40:33.250 --> 00:40:37.089
far as general nursing,
though, like as far as RNs,

00:40:37.089 --> 00:40:39.130
I would say if it's higher,
it's not much higher.

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:40.200
I mean, I don't know the
specific number [INAUDIBLE],

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:41.697
but it's certainly
not much higher.

00:40:41.697 --> 00:40:43.530
The numbers are pretty
low across the board.

00:40:43.530 --> 00:40:45.490
I mean, there's just
no way around that.

00:40:45.490 --> 00:40:46.750
Yeah.

00:40:46.750 --> 00:40:48.370
I'll have to go
look that up though.

00:40:48.370 --> 00:40:49.870
See, I was always
told that when you

00:40:49.870 --> 00:40:51.050
come to Google that
people are going to ask

00:40:51.050 --> 00:40:52.140
you questions and you're not
coming up with the answer,

00:40:52.140 --> 00:40:53.700
and you've got to
do your homework.

00:40:53.700 --> 00:40:54.818
So thank you.

00:40:54.818 --> 00:40:56.570
[LAUGH]

