Any other questions?

00:40:58.180 --> 00:40:59.360
Yeah, you have another one?

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:01.401
AUDIENCE: So you said that
you're a psychiatrist.

00:41:01.401 --> 00:41:03.980
DAMON TWEEDY: That's correct.

00:41:03.980 --> 00:41:05.520
AUDIENCE: There
seems to be-- and I

00:41:05.520 --> 00:41:11.790
also-- on my side of the
family have some family

00:41:11.790 --> 00:41:14.550
history of mental illness.

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:18.700
And so there's a shortage
of psychiatrists,

00:41:18.700 --> 00:41:21.490
and there just seems to
be not that many people

00:41:21.490 --> 00:41:25.299
going into psychiatry,
black, white, or green.

00:41:25.299 --> 00:41:27.590
So what-- and you may have
covered this, but I'm sorry.

00:41:27.590 --> 00:41:28.490
I came in late.

00:41:28.490 --> 00:41:30.977
How did you choose psychiatry
over the other specialties?

00:41:30.977 --> 00:41:32.810
DAMON TWEEDY: That's a
really good question.

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:35.640
Because within medicine,
psychiatry in many ways

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:36.730
is kind of marginalized.

00:41:36.730 --> 00:41:39.610
I mean, every walk of life has
their own hierarchy, right?

00:41:39.610 --> 00:41:42.150
So there's a hierarchy
within medicine as well,

00:41:42.150 --> 00:41:44.640
and psychiatrists are often
in some ways marginalized.

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:46.660
So when I first went
to medical school,

00:41:46.660 --> 00:41:48.980
I never thought I would
be a psychiatrist.

00:41:48.980 --> 00:41:51.460
I thought I was going to
be a cardiologist, a heart

00:41:51.460 --> 00:41:51.980
specialist.

00:41:51.980 --> 00:41:53.780
That's what I was really-- I
had done research in that field.

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:55.738
I had a lot of family
history of heart disease.

00:41:55.738 --> 00:41:57.996
And so that was where
I was really going to.

00:41:57.996 --> 00:42:00.390
And even after medical
school, I actually

00:42:00.390 --> 00:42:01.900
started my first--
actually matched

00:42:01.900 --> 00:42:04.110
into a program that was
going to put me on that path.

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:05.120
I started in the
general medicine

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:07.536
path, which is where you go
before you go into cardiology.

00:42:07.536 --> 00:42:09.830
So I was all on that
trajectory all the way through.

00:42:09.830 --> 00:42:11.790
And then about halfway
through the year,

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:14.079
you're getting patients that
are admitted to your team

00:42:14.079 --> 00:42:15.370
from all parts of the hospital.

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:16.960
And some of them-- a lot of
them have mental health issues.

00:42:16.960 --> 00:42:18.660
But they were still sick
enough where they needed

00:42:18.660 --> 00:42:20.080
to be on the medical service.

00:42:20.080 --> 00:42:22.982
And something about working
with some of those folks

00:42:22.982 --> 00:42:25.190
and realizing there's this
great need to help people,

00:42:25.190 --> 00:42:26.790
it really just
appealed to me in a way

00:42:26.790 --> 00:42:27.480
that I never thought it would.

00:42:27.480 --> 00:42:29.350
Because I didn't like psychiatry
much in medical school.

00:42:29.350 --> 00:42:31.210
I did a rotation at a hospital
and didn't care for it

00:42:31.210 --> 00:42:31.460
that much.

00:42:31.460 --> 00:42:33.630
But there's something about
that particular setting

00:42:33.630 --> 00:42:34.480
where I was at.

00:42:34.480 --> 00:42:36.370
And people started to tell
me that I had an attitude.

00:42:36.370 --> 00:42:38.619
Like, I would be able to get
information from patients

00:42:38.619 --> 00:42:40.590
that other doctors
weren't able to get.

00:42:40.590 --> 00:42:41.870
Like, people were
connecting with me in a way

00:42:41.870 --> 00:42:43.150
that they weren't
with other doctors.

00:42:43.150 --> 00:42:44.820
Which is all surprising
to me, because I never

00:42:44.820 --> 00:42:46.940
considered myself this great
social person or anything.

00:42:46.940 --> 00:42:49.170
But people were sort of
connecting to me in that way,

00:42:49.170 --> 00:42:51.180
and that really kind
of got me thinking

00:42:51.180 --> 00:42:52.770
that maybe I could do this.

00:42:52.770 --> 00:42:55.261
And so that's really how
I got into psychiatry.

00:42:55.261 --> 00:42:56.760
It's a huge problem
as far as access

00:42:56.760 --> 00:42:59.200
to care for psychiatrists
across the board.

00:42:59.200 --> 00:43:01.130
It's a huge problem.

00:43:01.130 --> 00:43:02.811
If you tie back
the race, there's

00:43:02.811 --> 00:43:05.310
a huge stigma within the African
American community in terms

00:43:05.310 --> 00:43:06.260
of mental health treatment.

00:43:06.260 --> 00:43:07.176
There's a huge stigma.

00:43:07.176 --> 00:43:09.990
So the numbers of black people
seeking mental health care,

00:43:09.990 --> 00:43:12.704
it's a big issue that
I'm dealing with.

00:43:12.704 --> 00:43:14.120
So there's so many
layers to that.

00:43:14.120 --> 00:43:19.390
I mean, part of it is how
psychiatrists are-- again,

00:43:19.390 --> 00:43:20.610
the perception of it.

00:43:20.610 --> 00:43:22.100
There's sort of this stigma.

00:43:22.100 --> 00:43:23.740
Many times, it was
funded separately.

00:43:23.740 --> 00:43:25.152
So the mental
health [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:25.152 --> 00:43:27.610
It would be medical care, and
people would separate it out.

00:43:27.610 --> 00:43:29.950
And that's further sort of
stigmatizing the mental health

00:43:29.950 --> 00:43:30.450
treatment.

00:43:30.450 --> 00:43:31.979
So there's so many
factors at work.

00:43:31.979 --> 00:43:34.520
There's supposed to be-- I know
they passed the Mental Health

00:43:34.520 --> 00:43:35.910
Parity Act, and the
Affordable Care Act

00:43:35.910 --> 00:43:37.826
is supposed to help with
some of these issues.

00:43:37.826 --> 00:43:39.050
All that remains to be seen.

00:43:39.050 --> 00:43:41.130
I think it's still a big
issue, and then hopefully it'll

00:43:41.130 --> 00:43:41.720
be getting better.

00:43:41.720 --> 00:43:42.840
But it's a huge problem.

00:43:42.840 --> 00:43:44.050
You see it every day.

00:43:44.050 --> 00:43:46.050
AUDIENCE: I just wonder
if you have any thoughts

00:43:46.050 --> 00:43:48.900
about the separation between
medicine and dentistry,

00:43:48.900 --> 00:43:51.410
and whether you're aware
of how any of these

00:43:51.410 --> 00:43:54.150
issues that you talked about
our different or the same

00:43:54.150 --> 00:43:57.199
in dentistry, or whether
that wall affects things?

00:43:57.199 --> 00:43:57.990
DAMON TWEEDY: Yeah.

00:43:57.990 --> 00:44:01.540
So the issues are pretty
similar, actually.

00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:03.790
If you're talking about
issues around race and poverty

00:44:03.790 --> 00:44:05.940
and access to care, in
some ways they're worse.

00:44:05.940 --> 00:44:07.820
I mean, in some
ways, dentistry's

00:44:07.820 --> 00:44:10.572
often like-- finding an
affordable dentist is

00:44:10.572 --> 00:44:12.530
almost like finding an
affordable psychiatrist.

00:44:12.530 --> 00:44:14.325
Those are really
difficult things to do.

00:44:14.325 --> 00:44:16.700
So in some ways, it's even
worse than in general medicine

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:19.033
actually, when you're talking
about from the perspective

00:44:19.033 --> 00:44:20.534
of poverty and race.

00:44:20.534 --> 00:44:22.825
In terms of numbers of minority
providers and all that,

00:44:22.825 --> 00:44:24.860
it's even worse.

00:44:24.860 --> 00:44:26.730
As far as why they're
separated, yeah,

00:44:26.730 --> 00:44:27.920
that I'm not so sure about.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:30.700
The historical basis
for separating them out,

00:44:30.700 --> 00:44:31.860
that I'm not so sure about.

00:44:31.860 --> 00:44:34.540
But the issues are still very
pertinent, very relevant.

00:44:34.540 --> 00:44:35.927
No doubt about that.

00:44:35.927 --> 00:44:37.010
It's so amazing, actually.

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:38.850
You'll see patients in
the medical setting,

00:44:38.850 --> 00:44:41.145
and they have all these
[INAUDIBLE] health problems,

00:44:41.145 --> 00:44:43.270
but you can clearly see
they have dental needs that

00:44:43.270 --> 00:44:44.290
need to be addressed.

00:44:44.290 --> 00:44:45.969
And then trying
to find something

00:44:45.969 --> 00:44:48.260
that they-- care they can
receive is just unbelievable.

00:44:48.260 --> 00:44:51.720
The waits for them to get care
for dental problems, I mean,

00:44:51.720 --> 00:44:53.045
we're talking several months.

00:44:53.045 --> 00:44:54.756
I mean, months and
months and months.

00:44:54.756 --> 00:44:56.130
Some would have
to come in, like,

00:44:56.130 --> 00:44:58.835
with just a raging infection
to get any kind of treatment.

00:44:58.835 --> 00:45:00.490
You had to be really sick
to get treatment, which

00:45:00.490 --> 00:45:01.450
is sort of perverse, right?

00:45:01.450 --> 00:45:02.991
Because the whole
point is to sort of

00:45:02.991 --> 00:45:05.290
prevent these problems
from happening.

00:45:05.290 --> 00:45:07.030
And dentistry's
sometimes even worse.

00:45:07.030 --> 00:45:08.934
That's been my
experience anyway.

00:45:08.934 --> 00:45:09.860
Yeah.

00:45:09.860 --> 00:45:10.560
Absolutely.

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:11.580
Great.

